  "exemplar_id": "ex_vertigo_001",
  "frozen": true,
  "context_summary": "47-year-old woman presents with episodes of the room spinning over the past week. She hasn't yet described how long each episode lasts or what triggers it, and there's no information yet on associated hearing changes. The doctor is trying to work out whether this fits BPPV, vestibular neuritis, or Meniere's disease before deciding on exam maneuvers and treatment.",
  "good_next_question": "When the spinning happens, does it only last a few seconds and come on with a specific head movement, or does it last for hours at a time, or has it been spinning constantly without any letup?",
  "rationale": "The duration and triggering pattern of vertigo is the single most powerful discriminator among the three leading causes of this presentation. BPPV episodes are brief, typically seconds and rarely over a minute, strictly triggered by head position change, and resolve completely between episodes. Meniere's disease produces episodic vertigo lasting 20 minutes to several hours, usually clustered with unilateral hearing loss, tinnitus, and aural fullness. Vestibular neuritis causes a single prolonged, constant vertigo lasting days, unrelated to position, often following a viral illness, without auditory symptoms. Getting this timeline right determines the next bedside step, a Dix-Hallpike maneuver for suspected BPPV, and the treatment approach, canalith repositioning versus vestibular suppressants and steroids versus diuretics and salt restriction, so it's more useful than asking about associated symptoms first, since duration and pattern narrow the differential before symptom-specific questions are even needed.",
  "tags": [
    "ent",
    "vertigo",
    "bppv",
    "vestibular_neuritis",
    "menieres",
    "adult",
    "dizziness"
  ],
